text: Wow - a great movie with a very powerful theological message. It‚Äôs not popular because it‚Äôs a cerebral SciFi movie with no aliens or space battles. In their great and expensive quest to find intelligent alien life, they find ‚Ä¶. none. The best line of the movie is when Brad Pitt says something along the lines of ‚ÄúThey only saw what wasn‚Äôt there and missed what was staring them in the face‚Äù.   We witness an increasingly frantic and futile search for intelligent alien life in the real world and miss what‚Äôs staring us in the face - i.e., a powerful cosmological argument for the existence of God. A very compelling movie and one of the best SciFy flicks I‚Äôve seen. Highly recommended.

text: I'm amazed at the audience reception to this. Usually, audience scores go against the critical grain. You'll find films that are, really, quite bad by all accounts but still enjoyable. They can be surprise hits. Venom is a great example. It's not a good film. But is is diverting enough to be fun and it was popular. "Ad Astra" was lauded by many critics... But the wider audience was completely indifferent. Which is crazy to me because it's a great film with a lot going on. Was it too open to interpretation? I wouldn't suggest that the film was too intelligent and thought provoking for the masses... But... Nah, it probably was

text: I think of new movies like meeting new people. I give everyone a chance. Sure, I've heard good things, bad things, horrible, wonderful, creepy, ridiculous things. I make up my own mind. I may meet a bad boss who is a great friend, or a great boss who is a horrible friend. My thoughts about that person depend on whether I'm an employee or a friend. LoL if you like the actors in this movie, if you're okay with a slow build and characters without a lot of charisma that are still likeable, see this movie. Give it a clean slate. I won't spoil the movie, but I will give you some peace of mind, it had a definite ending. It doesn't just build up to the climax and go black. That was my biggest concern. I don't really like ambiguity. :) I hope you enjoy the scenery and appreciate the physical toll it must have taken to do these scenes. At the very least, you get to see some really cool planets and space scenery. :)  I'd like to add, for the people who are critical of the acting. My understanding is, it's hard enough to act when you have actual people and an environment to interact with/react to. I think these actors did a phenomenal job with a green screen and situations they have obviously never actually encountered.   (I'm so bored with a world where MOST PEOPLE HAVE A "red pen"  at the ready to correct everyone else, whenever possible.) I rarely write reviews, but all of the critical reviews just... Idk, got under my skin. Lol I feel better now.   Summary: A MOVIE, it's FICTION. Sticklers for scientific accuracy need not apply.
